## Question 3: Why we study amygdala and fear?

When we experience fear feelings in real world or artificial environment (viewing of fearful or angry faces) activates human amygdala. Often this amygdala activation is increased in fear-related disorders.

Experiencing an extremely traumatic event— either experiencing it or witnessing it, such as combat or violent assault, can lead to Post-traumatic stress disorder (PTSD). PTSD is the fourth most common psychiatric diagnosis and is defined by three primary symptom clusters after an event that elicited fear, helplessness or horror. Symptoms may include flashbacks, nightmares and severe anxiety, as well as uncontrollable thoughts about the event.

Jon Snow might already had PTSD which he doesn't realize.

问题3：为什么我们研究杏仁核和恐惧？

当我们在现实世界或人造环境（观看恐惧或愤怒的面孔）中遇到恐惧感时，激活人类的扁桃体。 通常，这种杏仁核激活在恐惧相关疾病中增加。

经历极度创伤的事件 - 无论是经历或目睹它，如战斗或暴力袭击，都可能导致创伤后应激障碍（PTSD）。 PTSD是第四大最常见的精神病诊断，并且在引发恐惧，无助或恐怖的事件之后由三个主要症状簇定义。 症状可能包括闪回，恶梦和严重的焦虑，以及对事件无法控制的想法。

Jon Snow可能已经有PTSD，他没有意识到。

## Question 4: Is Amygdala = Fear?

问题4：杏仁核=恐惧？

![](media/15065989759397/15066038902481.jpg)


The beloved Dr. Joseph LeDoux said, The Amygdala Is Not the Brain’s Fear Center.

One of the first things a scientist learns is that a correlation does not necessarily reveal causation. The interpretation that the amygdala is the brain’s fear center confuses correlation and causation.

The idea that the amygdala is the home of fear in the brain is just that—an idea. It is not a scientific finding but instead a conclusion based on an interpretation of a finding.

约瑟夫·勒杜克博士说，杏仁人不是大脑的恐惧中心。

科学家首先学到的一个因素是，相关性并不一定揭示因果关系。 解释说，杏仁核是大脑的恐惧中心混淆了相关性和因果关系。

杏仁核是大脑中恐惧的家园的想法就是这个想法。 这不是一个科学的发现，而是基于对一个发现的解释的结论。

## Question 5: So what is the finding, what is the interpretation, and how did the interpretation come about?

The Finding: When the amygdala is damaged, previously threatening stimuli come to be treated as benign. The classic discovery was that monkeys with amygdala damage were “tamed;” snakes, for example, no longer elicited so-called fight-flight responses after amygdala damage. Later studies in rats mapped out the amygdala’s role in a neural system that detects and responds to threats, and similar circuits were found to be operative when the human brain processes threats.

问题5：那么发现是什么，解释是什么，怎么解释呢？

发现：当杏仁核损坏时，以前威胁的刺激被认为是良性的。 经典的发现是，具有杏仁核损伤的猴子被“驯服”，例如，在杏仁核损伤后，不再引发所谓的打击飞行反应。 后来的大鼠研究绘制了杏仁核在检测和应对威胁的神经系统中的作用，当人类大脑处理威胁时，类似的电路被发现是有效的。

![](media/15065989759397/15066039273379.jpg)


The Interpretation: Since damage to the amygdala eliminates behavioral responses to threats, feelings of “fear” are products of the amygdala. People are indeed less responsive to threats when the amygdala is damaged (in humans amygdala damage can occur as a result of epilepsy or other medical conditions or their surgical treatment). Yet, these people can still experience (feel) “fear.” In other words, the amygdala is an important part of the circuit that allows the brain to detect and respond to threats but is not necessary to feel “fear.”

Take-home message: The conclusion that the amygdala is the brain’s fear center wrongly assumes that the feelings of “fear” and the responses elicited by threats are products of the same brain system. While amygdala circuits are directly responsible for behavioral/physiological responses elicited by threats, they are not directly responsible for feelings of “fear.”

解释：由于对杏仁核的损害消除了对威胁的行为反应，“恐惧”的感觉是杏仁核的产物。 当杏仁核被破坏时，人们确实对威胁的反应能力较差（在人类中，由于癫痫或其他医疗条件或其手术治疗，可能会导致杏仁体损伤）。 然而，这些人仍然可以体验（感觉）“恐惧”。换句话说，杏仁体是电路的一个重要组成部分，它允许大脑检测和应对威胁，但不必感到“恐惧”。

回归信息：杏仁核是大脑恐惧中心的结论错误地假设“恐惧”的感觉和威胁引发的反应是同一脑系统的产物。 虽然杏仁核线路对威胁引起的行为/生理反应负直接责任，但它们对“恐惧”的感觉并不直接负责。

## Question 6: If amygdala is not the fear center, how does amygdala contribute to non-conscious aspects of fear?

LeDoux's research suggested that the amygdala contributes to non-conscious aspects of fear, by which I meant the detection of threats and the control of body responses that help cope with the threat. Conscious fear, I argued, is a product of cognitive systems in the neocortex that operate in parallel with the amygdala circuit.

问题6：如果杏仁核不是恐惧中心，那么杏仁核如何促成恐惧的非意识方面呢？

LeDoux的研究表明，杏仁核有助于恐惧的非意识方面，我的意思是检测威胁和控制身体反应，以应对威胁。 我认为，意识到的恐惧是新皮质中与杏仁核电路并行运行的认知系统的产物。

![](media/15065989759397/15066039554110.jpg)


Be suspicious of any statement that says a brain area is a center responsible for some function.

Amygdala is involved in fear acquisition, consolidation, expression, retrieval, extinction, reconsolidation, renewal, reinstatement, spontaneous recovery, etc.

RELAX, I‘m not going to give you details about that.

The take-home message is: Amygdala is a key brain nucleus for fear learning and memory.

怀疑任何声称脑区是负责某些功能的中心。

杏仁核参与恐惧获取，巩固，表达，检索，灭绝，重新整合，更新，复原，自发恢复等。

放松，我不会给你细节。

回归信息是：杏仁核是恐惧学习和记忆的关键脑核。

## Question 7: What is learned fear?

I will introduce two most fundamental forms of amygdala dependent learning --- classical (Pavlovian) and instrumental (operant) conditioning.

I know they are classical theories and have long been studied in humans and animals. I still believe they are the fundamental models of emotional learning for AI in the future.

Although Ivan Pavlov won a Nobel Prize for studying digestion, he is much more famous for something else: “Pavlov’s dog”. Classical (or Pavlovian) conditioning is one of the fundamental ways we learn about the world around us. But it is far more than just a theory of learning; it is also arguably a theory of identity.

问题7：什么是学到的恐惧？

我将介绍两种最基本的杏仁核依赖学习形式 - 古典（巴甫洛维）和工具（操作）条件。

我知道他们是古典理论，长期以来一直在人类和动物学习。 我仍然相信他们是未来AI的情感学习的基本模式。

尽管伊万·巴甫洛夫获得了诺贝尔文学研究的消息，但他更加着名：“巴甫洛夫的狗”。 古典（或巴甫洛夫）条件是我们了解我们周边世界的基本方法之一。 但这不仅仅是学习的理论， 也可以说是身份认同理论。

![](media/15065989759397/15066039999685.jpg)


In his famous experiment, Pavlov rang a bell and then gave a dog some food. After repeating this pairing multiple times, the dog eventually treated the bell as a signal for food, and began salivating in anticipation of the treat. This kind of result has been reproduced in the lab using a wide range of signals (e.g., tones, light, tastes, settings) paired with many different events besides food (e.g., drugs, shocks, illness; etc).

在他着名的实验中，巴甫洛夫响了一声钟，然后给了狗一些食物。 在多次重复配对之后，狗最终将钟作为食物的信号，并开始唾液预期的治疗。 这种结果已经在实验室中使用与食物（例如药物，冲击，疾病等）之外的许多不同事件配对的各种信号（例如，音调，光，口味，设置）而再现。

![](media/15065989759397/15066040097811.jpg)


![](media/15065989759397/15066040143926.jpg)


![](media/15065989759397/15066040239869.jpg)


![](media/15065989759397/15066040305477.jpg)


In a general way, classical conditioning occurs whenever neutral stimuli are associated with psychologically significant events. The dog food in Pavlov’s experiment is called the unconditioned stimulus (US) because it elicits an unconditioned response (UR). That is, without any kind of “training” or “teaching,” the stimulus produces a natural or instinctual reaction.

A conditioned stimulus (CS) is a signal that has no importance to the organism until it is paired with something that does have importance. For example, in Pavlov’s experiment, the bell is the conditioned stimulus. Before the dog has learned to associate the bell (CS) with the presence of food (US), hearing the bell means nothing to the dog. However, after multiple pairings of the bell with the presentation of food, the dog starts to drool at the sound of the bell. This drooling in response to the bell is the conditioned response (CR).

A large body of literature has established that associative learning requires the amygdala, where CS-US conjunction occurs.

一般来说，只要中性刺激与心理重要事件有关，就会发生经典的调理。巴甫洛夫的实验中的狗食被称为无条件的刺激（美国），因为它引发了无条件的反应（UR）。也就是说，没有任何一种“训练”或“教学”，刺激就会产生自然或本能的反应。

条件刺激（CS）是一种对生物体没有重要性的信号，直到与具有重要性的物质配对。例如，在巴甫洛夫的实验中，钟是条件刺激。在狗已经学会将钟声（CS）与食物（US）的存在联系之前，听到铃声对狗没有任何意义。然而，在多次配对的钟声与食物的介绍之后，狗开始流口水的钟声。响应钟声的这种流口水是条件反应（CR）。

大量的文学证明，联想学习需要杏仁核，其中发生CS-US连接。

![](media/15065989759397/15066040535902.jpg)


Which also related to the development of fear-related disorders.

这也与恐惧相关疾病的发展有关。

![](media/15065989759397/15066040627731.jpg)


Robert A. Rescorla provided a clear summary of this change in thinking, and its implications, in his 1988 article "Pavlovian conditioning: It's not what you think it is”.

Although classical conditioning is a powerful explanation for how we learn many different things, there is a second form of conditioning that also helps explain how we learn. First studied by Edward Thorndike, and later extended by B. F. Skinner, this second type of conditioning is known as instrumental or operant conditioning.

Robert A. Rescorla在1988年的文章“帕夫洛维亚条件：这不是你的想法”中，提供了这种思维变化及其影响的明确总结。

虽然古典条件是我们如何学习许多不同的东西的强大的解释，但第二种形式的调理也有助于解释我们如何学习。 爱德华·索恩迪克（Edward Thorndike）首先研究过，后来被B.F. Skinner扩展，第二种类型的调理被称为工具或操作条件。

![](media/15065989759397/15066040775640.jpg)


![](media/15065989759397/15066040823199.jpg)


![](media/15065989759397/15066040869927.jpg)


Operant conditioning occurs when a behavior (as opposed to a stimulus) is associated with the occurrence of a significant event. In the best-known example, a rat in a laboratory learns to press a lever in a cage (called a “Skinner box”) to receive food. Because the rat has no “natural” association between pressing a lever and getting food, the rat has to learn this connection. At first, the rat may simply explore its cage, climbing on top of things, burrowing under things, in search of food. Eventually while poking around its cage, the rat accidentally presses the lever, and a food pellet drops in. This voluntary behavior is called an operant behavior, because it “operates” on the environment (i.e., it is an action that the animal itself makes).

Once the rat recognizes that it receives a piece of food every time it presses the lever, the behavior of lever-pressing becomes reinforced. That is, the food pellets serve as reinforcers because they strengthen the rat’s desire to engage with the environment in this particular manner.

According to Thorndike’s law of effect, when a behavior has a positive (satisfying) effect or consequence, it is likely to be repeated in the future. However, when a behavior has a negative (painful/annoying) consequence, it is less likely to be repeated in the future. Effects that increase behaviors are referred to as reinforcers, and effects that decrease them are referred to as punishers.

https://courses.lumenlearning.com/wsu-sandbox/

After conditioning, the response to the CS can be eliminated if the CS is presented repeatedly without the US. This effect is called extinction, and the response is said to become “extinguished.”

当行为（与刺激相反））与重大事件的发生相关联时，发生操作调节。在众所周知的例子中，实验室的一只老鼠学会把笼子里的一个杠杆（叫做“Skinner盒子”）拿来接受食物。因为大鼠在按压杠杆和获得食物之间没有“自然”关系，所以大鼠必须学习这种联系。起初，大鼠可以简单地探索笼子，爬上事物，挖掘事物，寻找食物。最后，当鼠标在笼子周围时，大鼠意外按下杠杆，食物颗粒掉落。这种自愿行为被称为操作行为，因为它在环境中“操作”（即动物本身所起作用的动作） ）。

一旦大鼠认识到，每次按压手柄时，它会收到一块食物，杠杆按压的行为就会加强。也就是说，食物颗粒作为强化剂，因为它们增强了大鼠以这种特殊方式与环境接触的愿望。

根据Thorndike的效应定律，当某种行为具有积极（令人满意的）效果或后果时，将来可能会重复。然而，当一种行为产生负面（痛苦/烦人的）后果时，在将来不太可能重复。增加行为的效果被称为强化剂，减少它们的效果被称为惩罚者。

https://courses.lumenlearning.com/wsu-sandbox/

调节后，如果没有美国的CS反复提供CS，则可以消除对CS的响应。这种效应被称为灭绝，反应被称为“熄灭”。

![](media/15065989759397/15066041299443.jpg)


![](media/15065989759397/15066041357864.jpg)


Extinction is important for many reasons. For one thing, it is the basis for many therapies that clinical psychologists use to eliminate maladaptive and pathological fear.

But extinction is not erasing the fear memory but creating a new memory, which means the fear memory can return in multiple ways.

That’s why I start to study innate fear to answer this question during my postdoc.

I choose Dr. Kerry Ressler and Dr. Vadim Bolshakov as my mentors, not only because of they are the expertise in this field.

But also have unlimited fundings.

许多原因灭绝是重要的。 一方面，它是临床心理学家用来消除适应不良和病理恐惧的许多疗法的基础。

但灭绝并不是消除恐惧记忆，而是创造一个新的记忆，这意味着恐惧记忆可以以多种方式返回。

这就是为什么我开始研究天生的恐惧来回答这个问题在我的博士后。

我选择克里·雷斯勒博士和博迪姆博尔什科夫博士作为我的导师，不仅因为他们是这方面的专长。

但也有无限的资金。

## Question 8: What is innate fear?

As we know, ‘learned fear’ that is elicited by neutral stimuli that have been associated with innate threats, the plasticity that is strong enough for rapid learning of new CS-US association causes rapid overwriting of existing memories.

‘Innate fear’ responses that are activated by intrinsically threatening stimuli, innate behaviors are genetically determined and stereotyped, the innate circuits can be accessed repeatedly without change.

This is much easier to understand.

If you are a mice living outside of the laboratory. Your innate fear resources come from…

问题8：天生的恐惧是什么？

据我们所知，由于与天生威胁相关的中性刺激所引起的“学到的恐惧”，对于新的CS-US协会的快速学习而言足够强大的可塑性导致现有记忆的快速覆盖。

通过内在威胁的刺激，先天行为激活的“先天的恐惧”反应是基因决定和定型的，可以重复访问固有的电路而不改变。

这更容易理解。

如果你是住在实验室外的小鼠。 你天生的恐惧资源来自...

